{"id":14880777,"mediaExerciseId":"1d935d33-643b-40d7-a2b0-df6f7be49e25","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"3.1","sectionTitle":"Cash Flow and Financial Statements:A Closer Look","pageNumber":54,"solutions":[{"id":5662377,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this question, we must define and give three examples of a cash source and use of cash. \n\nLet's first determine what is a cash source and provide some examples.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/ff97610e42f199e16013e816d3d4a18e/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/ff97610e42f199e16013e816d3d4a18e/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **cash source** is any activity that increases the cash of a business. A good indication of a source of cash is a decrease in an asset account or an increase in a liability (or equity) account, which we can observe on a company's comparative balance sheet.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/8ca142bbc63f78f1dc16eb7a69ec613f/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/8ca142bbc63f78f1dc16eb7a69ec613f/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"To provide an example of a cash source, here are three instances wherein the cash of an entity increases:\n\n1. **Increase in accounts payable**\nPurchases on account indicate an increase in accounts payable. When a purchase is made on account, it does not immediately expend cash, thus creating a positive cash flow effect.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/51575dec220286618cc64f9692d10640/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/51575dec220286618cc64f9692d10640/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"2. **Increase in common stock**\nIssuance of the common stock is an investing activity that increases the company's capital, raising the business's cash.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":99,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/480af2d03536bbfc5523418a0bd272b5/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":50,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/480af2d03536bbfc5523418a0bd272b5/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"3. **Increase in retained earnings** \nRetained earnings are the cash amount leftover after deducting the dividends from the company's net income. An increase in retained earnings also increases the cash of the company by the exact amount.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/31fc3c0c07a0e7e61b6d7fb78fa04640/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/31fc3c0c07a0e7e61b6d7fb78fa04640/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"In the second part, we are asked to define the cash uses or applications and provide examples of such.\n\nA **cash use or application** is any activity wherein the entity expends its cash. An entity's increase in assets or decrease in liability (or equity) accounts can mainly indicate a reduction in cash. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/1377c2670e2841310fdaecbc07261fef/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/1377c2670e2841310fdaecbc07261fef/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"To provide an example of cash use and applications, here are three instances wherein the cash of an entity decreases:\n\n1. **Increase in accounts receivable**\nAs opposed to an increase in account payable providing a positive cash flow, an increase in accounts receivables results in a negative cash flow effect as a customer did not yet pay in cash the credited sales of the business.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":211,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/c0287517a1e17fd7da66366deb2b4ca1/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":108,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/c0287517a1e17fd7da66366deb2b4ca1/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"2. **Increase in inventory**\nAn increase in inventory indicates an outlay of cash to purchase inventory items, resulting in a decrease in cash for the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/f5c795f01527331b91de906f683ccc19/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/f5c795f01527331b91de906f683ccc19/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8},{"columns":[{"text":"3. **Decrease in notes payable**\nCash is applied to pay long-term loans, mortgages, any other financial liabilities.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/91d68e3e1c383d48b3f3ba62f53c07fe/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/17/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/91d68e3e1c383d48b3f3ba62f53c07fe/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":9},{"columns":[{"text":"To sum up everything, a cash source is the inflow of money to the entity, while on the other hand, a cash use is the outflow of cash to an entity. \n\nA key indicator to identify whether a transaction is a cash source or use is that a cash source is often characterized by a decrease in assets and increase in liability (or equity), and vice versa for a cash use or application.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/13/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/217c28daaf3b132ceb071c3df8f6003f/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/13/87d2bd891230a00579bf77fe2d85c84f/217c28daaf3b132ceb071c3df8f6003f/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":10}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"7c779db8-26f8-4ac8-b0a1-27cc24e37ae2","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":10},{"id":5950425,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This problem requires us to identify the sources and uses of cash and provide three examples of each. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/fc361f79c0c68d57f98294f2e8b22e8d/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/fc361f79c0c68d57f98294f2e8b22e8d/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 1a\n**Sources of cash** refers to the activities that provide *cash inflow* to the entity. These are activities that generate cash.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The examples of activities that are considered as **sources of cash** are the following. \n1. Selling a product- product or service is sold in exchange for cash. \n2. Selling an asset- the disposal of an asset provides cash to the entity. \n3. Selling security- cash is generated from borrowing or selling shares of stock in a market. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":176,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/a952a89d835135e3b697eec3267cbb5c/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":89,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/a952a89d835135e3b697eec3267cbb5c/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 1b\nThe **use or application of cash** are the activities that cause an *outflow of cash* from the entity. These are the activities that involve spending cash. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"The examples of activities that are considered as **uses of cash** are the following. \n1. Cash flow to creditors- results from the payment of the company's debt.\n2. Cash flow to owners- cash is paid to owners in the form of dividends. \n3. Payment of materials/labor- cash is paid to suppliers of materials and to the employees.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/8fd9820172dc85c7ddd9066510f04eb9/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/28/caf21ec152dfcfd85c808e2a8d677204/8fd9820172dc85c7ddd9066510f04eb9/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"bd3f329a-bbba-4c38-8ffa-422f5a63b33d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880778,"exerciseName":"2","page":57,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8099582c-0f8a-41d7-abb6-b11023aff1f9","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-exercises-2-8099582c-0f8a-41d7-abb6-b11023aff1f9"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880776,"exerciseName":"2","page":48,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a1406539-96c6-427f-8442-781c0ccc3372","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-exercises-2-a1406539-96c6-427f-8442-781c0ccc3372"},{"id":14880775,"exerciseName":"1","page":48,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"1ce39b70-a191-439d-8149-793d0c4eba62","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-exercises-1-1ce39b70-a191-439d-8149-793d0c4eba62"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-3-exercises-1-1d935d33-643b-40d7-a2b0-df6f7be49e25"}